SIMPLE: purchase
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Purchase
<hw>Pur"chase</hw> <pr>(?; 48)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Purchased</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Purchasing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>purchasen</ets>, <ets>porchacen</ets>, OF. <ets>porchacier</ets>,
<ets>purchacier</ets>, to pursue, to seek eagerly, F.
<ets>pourchasser</ets>; OF. <ets>pour</ets>, <ets>por</ets>,
<ets>pur</ets>, for (L. <ets>pro</ets>) + <ets>chacier</ets> to pursue,
to chase. See <er>Chase</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pursue and
obtain; to acquire by seeking; to gain, obtain, or acquire.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That loves the thing he can not <qex>purchase</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your accent is Something finer than you could <qex>purchase</qex>
in so removed a dwelling.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His faults . . . hereditary⟦br⟧
Rather than <qex>purchased</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To obtain by paying money or its equivalent; to buy
for a price; <as>as, to <ex>purchase</ex> land, or a
house</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The field which Abraham <qex>purchased</qex> of the sons of
Heth.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xxv. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To obtain by any outlay, as of labor, danger, or
sacrifice, etc.; <as>as, to <ex>purchase</ex> favor with
flattery</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One poor retiring minute . . . ⟦br⟧
Would <qex>purchase</qex> thee a thousand thousand friends.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A world who would not <qex>purchase</qex> with a bruise?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To expiate by a fine or forfeit.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not tears nor prayers shall <qex>purchase</qex> out abuses.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To acquire by any
means except descent or inheritance.</def> <au>Blackstone.</au>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>To buy for a price.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To apply to (anything) a device for obtaining a
mechanical advantage; to get a purchase upon, or apply a purchase to;
<as>as, to <ex>purchase</ex> a cannon</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purchase</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Purchase
<hw>Pur"chase</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put forth
effort to obtain anything; to strive; to exert one's self.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Duke John of Brabant <qex>purchased</qex> greatly that the Earl of
Flanders should have his daughter in marriage.</q> <rj><qau>Ld.
Berners.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To acquire wealth or property.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sure our lawyers⟦br⟧
Would not <qex>purchase</qex> half so fast.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Webster.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purchase</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Purchase
<hw>Pur"chase</hw> <pr>(?; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>purchds</ets>, F. <ets>pourchas</ets> eager pursuit. See
<er>Purchase</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
seeking, getting, or obtaining anything.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll . . . get meat to have thee,⟦br⟧
Or lose my life in the <qex>purchase</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. &
Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of seeking and acquiring property.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The acquisition of title to, or properly in,
anything for a price; buying for money or its equivalent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is foolish to lay out money in the <qex>purchase</qex> of
repentance.</q> <rj><qau>Franklin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which is obtained, got, or acquired, in any
manner, honestly or dishonestly; property; possession;
acquisition.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer. B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We met with little <qex>purchase</qex> upon this coast, except two
small vessels of Golconda.</q> <rj><qau>De Foe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A beauty-waning and distressed widow . . . ⟦br⟧
Made prize and <qex>purchase</qex> of his lustful eye.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>That which is obtained for a price in money or its
equivalent.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The scrip was complete evidence of his right in
the <xex>purchase</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Wheaton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Any mechanical hold, or advantage, applied to the
raising or removing of heavy bodies, as by a lever, a tackle, capstan,
and the like; also, the apparatus, tackle, or device by which the
advantage is gained.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A politician, to do great things, looks for a power -- what our
workmen call a <qex>purchase</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Acquisition of lands or tenements
by other means than descent or inheritance, namely, by one's own act or
agreement.</def> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Purchase criminal</b></col>, <cd>robbery.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Spenser.</au> -- <col><b>Purchase
money</b></col>, <cd>the money paid, or contracted to be paid, for
anything bought.</cd> <au>Berkeley.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>Worth [so
many] years' purchase</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>At [so many] years'
purchase</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a phrase by which the value or cost of a
thing is expressed in the length of time required for the income to
amount to the purchasing price; as, he bought the estate at a twenty
years' purchase. To say one's life is <col><b>not worth a day's
purchase</b></col> in the same as saying one will not live a day, or is
in imminent peril.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purchaser</ent>⟦br⟧
